This is a re-mix of Smight's lovely Vectored thrust VTOL (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4639577). I've added a peg hole to fit my hex flight stand (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4766450) as well as included a version of the engines with exhaust that won't need the flight peg. With the exhaust version, you'll need to print it twice with one copy mirrored and print the main body of the VTOL from the original design.

Please see the instructions at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4766450 for how I recommend printing the stand.

I had great success printing the aircraft itself on my Ender 3 by angling it up 45 degrees, which greatly reduced layer lines and gave it a clean underside.

If you like this, please consider a tip to Smight: https://www.thingiverse.com/smight/designs

This is a 6mm residential building for use with 6mm - 1/285 war games, such as Battletech and Epic 40k. It's designed to fix neatly within Battletech standard 33mm hexes like those found on the more recent maps at least.

I've tried to reduce the requirement for supports and on my print I can turn them off altogether on my Ender 3.

This is actually a sample from a much larger collection over here: https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/residential-buildings-for-6mm-1-285-scale-gaming. That collection currently includes over 160 buildings in four different styles and I'll continue to expand it in the future. 

 A free sample of the other style can be found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4688152.

I sell the complete collection to help justify the amount of time I spend doing this, but I think I have enough free models to game with.

Edit May 2021: I've uploaded a version of this model that is more resin friendly as I've removed all the internal geometry.

This is a sample of a collection of many gothic sci-fi buildings, for 6mm / 1:285 gaming - primarily Battletech and Epic 40k. I'm selling the full set on [cults3d here](https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/gothic-style-buildings-for-6mm-1-285-scale-gaming) to help justify to my significant other the time I spend working on these :)

The buildings are combinations of tower blocks that equate to level 1, 2 and 3 for when used within Battletech. There are two types of roof, flat and peeked as well as some other embellishments which means all up there are 290 different buildings in the cults3d set, although they're all different combinations of tower blocks.

For Battletech, they are designed to fit entirely within the "standard" Battletech map hexes of 33mm flat edge to flat edge as is used in the current boxed sets. The flat roof versions are also designed to allow Mech models to be placed on them.

The models are designed to be mostly supportless on an FDM printer and have printed fine on my Ender 3.

Edit:: I've repaired the files.

This is a reduced collection of [this set here](https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/hexagonal-residential-buildings-for-6mm-1-285-scale-gaming-tinnut) so that you can try them out.

In the distant future, humanity has learnt that hexagonal buildings are superior!

They're hexagonal residential buildings, for 6mm / 1:285 gaming - primarily Battletech but also Epic 40k and other games at that scale.

The buildings are combinations of hexagonal towers that equate to level 1, 2 and 3 within Battletech. I've set level 1 at about 25mm which allows small mechs to still see over them and level 2 at about 55mm which blocks visibility of even the largest mechs I've tested. Each level after that goes up 30mm.

They're designed to fit within the "standard" Battletech map hexes of 33mm flat edge to flat edge as is used in the current boxed sets. They also have a roof designed to allow Mech models to be placed on them.

The models are designed to be mostly supportless on an FDM printer and have printed fine on my Ender 3.

The two models shown are earlier test prints and the final models as uploaded include a couple of more details. I'll be replacing the images once I paint up one of the updated versions.

These were inspired by a few existing sets of Epic bases:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3176361
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:620563
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:676586
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2947509

There are round bases and rectangular bases. The round ones start from 10mm diameter (which is a bit too small for anything) to up 40mm diameter. Some of the smaller ones have a single peg/slot hole in them while the 25mm disks have 3 to 5 holes.

I created them in Tinkercad, which is quite handy for this kind of work.

As I need additional types I'll probably add more here.

I wanted rectangular bases for one side, and round bases for space bugs. Some of the holes are quite close to the edge and you may have problems printing them with larger nozzles - they work fine for me with a 0.25mm nozzle on my Ender 3.

This is my proxy design for an epic scale space bug Dactylis. I've based it off the fantastic design of a scratch built one in 40k scale that is on the internet - I'm afraid that mine doesn't do it justice but it was a lot of fun making it. Because of this it doesn't look anything like the original model that's well out of print.

To design it, I built the basic body shape in Tinkercad with simple shapes and then transferred that over to Blender and sculpted it heavily from there.

Work in progress - I haven't tried printing this just yet and it is missing some parts! Also, this is my first large model so I'm not sure if the cuts for will work.

This is meant as a proxy for a Battlefleet Gothic ship. It's a part based on the original miniature and part based on the RTS model.

It's currently missing its antenna (which I'm not a fan of) and I'm not too happy with how the bridge has turned out so I may re-do it.

Please do not upload this to Shapeways.

20/Mar/19 Edit: I fixed a small gap in the main hull but I had to redo all the body. I've also added a "whole body" model without the cannons or bridge in case anyone wants to cut it up themselves.
21/Mar/19 Edit: Added antenna and a modified bridge with holes for them.
23/Mar/19 Edit: I found some of the detail on the upper back was too small for 0.4mm nozzles so I redesigned those. With re-doing the cuts these might not be compatible with the earlier versions.
